Anonymous Fri 23 Apr 2021 15:37:16 No.38127910 Report
Quoted By: >>38128101
>>38126812
It's just traditional webcomic sickness. I used to read webcomics like they were crack, and I've seen this shit not happen only a handful of times. One was with a webcomic of which I don't recall the title, but which had atrocious art, so it was kind of easy to imagine how they kept up the pace. But really, it was kind of known back then, but that shit would not fly today. You could throw a rock into a crowd and hit a better artist. Then there's Endtown, which makes up for it by sheer volume and, seemingly, a lot of sheer luck during the first few arcs. I used to think Aaron planned shit out, but then the comic fell apart and I realized he just wings it. So he got lucky. Then there's Mare Internum, which is relatively short, and a self-contained story that moves along rather well. Of course, that was made by the author while on hiatus from her other webcomic, which moves at a glacial pace. Seriously, I haven't read it in a decade, and it's grown only by what was already there when I stopped. And then there's Unsounded, which is probably the only one that well and truly dodges this problem, which it does by keeping up a truly impressive pace and by rigorous plotting. And that comic is pretty old by now, too.

Clearly it's very, very hard to make a proper long form webcomic. There are comics out there that haven been running since the fucking late 90's, and they're still just flopping about.
